The Federal Capital Territory Administration (FCTA) has revealed that many vehicles in the Federal Capital Territory (FCT) are not road worthy, adding that out of the 103,919 vehicles inspected for roadworthiness in 2019 that 55,545 vehicles failed the test, representing 53.55 per cent of the failed vehicles. According to the report, out of the vehicles presented for inspection last year, only 48,274 vehicles, amounting to 46.45 per cent passed the test. Acting secretary, FCT Transportation Secretariat, Mrs. Alice Odey-Achu, who revealed this during an interaction with newsmen in Abuja yesterday, explained that the number of vehicles that failed the road worthy test were fairly used vehicles that were imported into the country with multiple defects. According to her, “The number of vehicles that failed the test is higher due to the following reasons; most imported fairly used vehicles, otherwise known as ‘tokumbo ‘ have one or more defects that were detected during the computerised inspections, which ordinarily cannot be detected during physical inspection. “Poor vehicle maintenance culture of most drivers and bad road network in the suburbs also contributed to defective vehicle components.” Odey-Achu however, revealed that the administration through the transportation secretariat generated over N3.4 billion from vehicle licensing, renewal of vehicle particulars, change of ownership and other sundry fees such as fines from various defaulters.